\title{"openai Docs"}

\taxon{skill}

\meta{description}{"Use when the user asks how to build with OpenAI products or APIs and needs up-to-date official documentation with citations (for example: Codex, Responses API, Chat Completions, Apps SDK, Agents SDK, Realtime, model capabilities or limits); prioritize OpenAI docs MCP tools and restrict any fallback browsing to official OpenAI domains."}

\subtree{
\title{OpenAI Docs}
\p{Provide authoritative, current guidance from OpenAI developer docs using the developers.openai.com MCP server. Always prioritize the developer docs MCP tools over web.run for OpenAI-related questions. Only if the MCP server is installed and returns no meaningful results should you fall back to web search.}

\subtree{
\title{Quick start}
\ul{
\li{Use \code{\startverb mcp\strong{openaiDeveloperDocs}search_openai_docs\stopverb} to find the most relevant doc pages.}
\li{Use \code{\startverb mcp\strong{openaiDeveloperDocs}fetch_openai_doc\stopverb} to pull exact sections and quote/paraphrase accurately.}
\li{Use \code{\startverb mcp\strong{openaiDeveloperDocs}list_openai_docs\stopverb} only when you need to browse or discover pages without a clear query.}
}
}

\subtree{
\title{OpenAI product snapshots}
\ol{
\li{Apps SDK: Build ChatGPT apps by providing a web component UI and an MCP server that exposes your app's tools to ChatGPT.}
\li{Responses API: A unified endpoint designed for stateful, multimodal, tool-using interactions in agentic workflows.}
\li{Chat Completions API: Generate a model response from a list of messages comprising a conversation.}
\li{Codex: OpenAI's coding agent for software development that can write, understand, review, and debug code.}
\li{gpt-oss: Open-weight OpenAI reasoning models (gpt-oss-120b and gpt-oss-20b) released under the Apache 2.0 license.}
\li{Realtime API: Build low-latency, multimodal experiences including natural speech-to-speech conversations.}
\li{Agents SDK: A toolkit for building agentic apps where a model can use tools and context, hand off to other agents, stream partial results, and keep a full trace.}
}
}

\subtree{
\title{If MCP server is missing}
\p{If MCP tools fail or no OpenAI docs resources are available:}

\ol{
\li{Run the install command yourself: \code{\startverb codex mcp add openaiDeveloperDocs --url https://developers.openai.com/mcp\stopverb}}
\li{If it fails due to permissions/sandboxing, immediately retry the same command with escalated permissions and include a 1-sentence justification for approval. Do not ask the user to run it yet.}
\li{Only if the escalated attempt fails, ask the user to run the install command.}
\li{Ask the user to restart Codex.}
\li{Re-run the doc search/fetch after restart.}
}
}

\subtree{
\title{Workflow}
\ol{
\li{Clarify the product scope (Codex, OpenAI API, or ChatGPT Apps SDK) and the task.}
\li{Search docs with a precise query.}
\li{Fetch the best page and the specific section needed (use \code{\startverb anchor\stopverb} when possible).}
\li{Answer with concise guidance and cite the doc source.}
\li{Provide code snippets only when the docs support them.}
}
}

\subtree{
\title{Quality rules}
\ul{
\li{Treat OpenAI docs as the source of truth; avoid speculation.}
\li{Keep quotes short and within policy limits; prefer paraphrase with citations.}
\li{If multiple pages differ, call out the difference and cite both.}
\li{If docs do not cover the user’s need, say so and offer next steps.}
}
}

\subtree{
\title{Tooling notes}
\ul{
\li{Always use MCP doc tools before any web search for OpenAI-related questions.}
\li{If the MCP server is installed but returns no meaningful results, then use web search as a fallback.}
\li{When falling back to web search, restrict to official OpenAI domains (developers.openai.com, platform.openai.com) and cite sources.}
}
}
}